PSO J011.0457+41.5548, luminous blue variable candidate

Comment from John Martin:

You can find the spectrum used to make the classification of PSO J011.0457+41.5548:
https://urldefense.com/v3/__http://etacar.umn.edu/LuminousStars/M31M33/M31stars.html__;!!DZ3fjg!_KMBOVItouYOC2aLM17P24NS6ioiU8XNWJEjLY57FgyNe4KrLYENrdtAdMl5Jgz5hFq6zkMJZcwu6tV4$  

That spectrum is from 2015.  There is no sign in that spectrum that it is undergoing an S Doradus type eruption or that it is an LBV in quiescence.  The most important thing to note there is that there are *no* P-cygni type absorption in the H and He lines in the spectrum of PSO J011.0457+41.5548.  Quiescent LBVs must have P-cygni absorption.  This looks like a typical early A-type supergiant, a YSG (yellow super giant) with some spectral contamination from an unresolved HII region.

I am leaning toward thinking that this star is something else and the variability observed for it is at least partly associated with the unresolved HII region.
